      "writtenOn": "2019-03-20T19:18:43Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The code that calls this is missing, but I assume it is called through RenderedCameraDevice, which creates an EGL context and a pbuffer surface.  It looks like virtualscene is doing roughly the same thing (indirectly through the RenderTarget abstraction):\n\n// Used to do the final blit to the FB\nstd::unique_ptr\u003cRenderTarget\u003e RenderTarget::createDefault(\n        Renderer\u0026 renderer,\n        const GLESv2Dispatch* gles2,\n        uint32_t width,\n        uint32_t height) {\n    return std::unique_ptr\u003cRenderTarget\u003e(\n            new RenderTarget(renderer, gles2, /* framebuffer */ 0, 0, Texture(), width, height));\n}\n\nvoid RenderTarget::bind() const {\n    mGles2-\u003eglBindFramebuffer(GL_FRAMEBUFFER,\n                              mFramebuffer);  // For createDefault(), this is 0\n    mGles2-\u003eglViewport(0, 0, mWidth, mHeight);\n}",
      "parentUuid": "277ce906_1cd9bde2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 170,
        "startChar": 4,
